n of underlying assumptions and cultural practices guiding European policymakers and postnational Europe, shedding light on current trends characterizing its politics and relations with others. The book also includes a fascinating comparison to developments in North America, where the United States has pursued more restrictive border control strategies since 9/11. As a broad survey of the origins, evolution, and implications of this remarkable development in European integration, Cultures of Border Control will be of interest to students and scholars of international relations and political geography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBorder securityzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aeurope, european, borders, immigration, politics, political, poli sci, science, frontier, sovereignty, territory, territorial, security, international, global, constructivism, pragmatism, culture, cultural, policymaker, postnational, policies, restrictions, 9/11, wartime, controversial, government, schengen agreement, 1980s, contemporary, modern, 20th century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022697786740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226977881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226977881/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles